\begin_layout Section
Overview
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Overview"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider a 
\emph on
small open economy
\emph default
 with a 
\emph on
fixed exchange rate
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
overlapping generations
\emph default
.
 Time is discrete, 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\{0,1,\dots\}$
\end_inset

 and the frequency is annual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Households
\emph default
 live for up to 
\begin_inset Formula $\#$
\end_inset

 periods, and their age is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 The age dependent mortality is 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{a}\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and the population and demographic structure is constant.
 Households exogenously search for jobs and supply labor, receive inheritances
 and choose consumption and savings to get utility from consumption and
 bequests.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
foreign economy
\emph default
 provides a fixed nominal rate of return, sell import goods at fixed prices,
 and have a demand curve for the domestic export good.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
production
\emph default
 in the economy is layered as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Production firms
\emph default
 rent
\emph on
 capital
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
labor
\emph default
 to produce the domestic output good.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Repacking firms
\emph default
 combine imported goods with the domestic output good to produce a consumption
 good, an investment good, and an export good.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Capital is rented from a 
\emph on
capital agency
\emph default
, which purchases the investment good to accumulate capital subject to adjustmen
t costs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Labor is rented from a 
\emph on
labor agency
\emph default
, which post vacancies a search-and-match labor market to purchase labor
 from the households.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All firms are price takers.
 Prices are thus flexible, except for wages which is determined by ad hoc
 bargaining.
 All 
\emph on
goods markets clear
\emph default
 and the matching process is determined by a 
\emph on
matching function
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is 
\emph on
perfect foresight
\emph default
 in the economy.
 I.e.
 the value of all current and future variables are known.
 This is a strong assumption, and in many ways the model should be considered
 a first order approximation to a full model with both idiosyncratic and
 aggregate risk.
 It can be relevant to introduce model elements, which proxy for the effects
 of risks.
 Utility-of-wealth can e.g.
 proxy for a precautionary saving motive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium path
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Equilibrium-path"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
equilibrium path
\emph default
 in the economy is a set of paths for all variables, which satisfies all
 accounting identities, optimal firm and household behavior in terms of
 first order conditions, and implies market clearing.
 When all variables are constant over time, the equilibrium path is a 
\emph on
steady state
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In terms of math, the model is just an 
\emph on
equation system
\emph default
 stacking the accounting identifies, first order conditions and market clearing
 conditions.
 If the economy is initially out of steady state, we solve for the equilibrium
 path by truncating the equation system to 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 periods.
 The assumption is that the economy has settled down to the steady state
 well before period 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, and we can assume variables from period 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 onward are at their steady state value.
 The economy can be out of steady state both because lagged 
\emph on
endogenous 
\emph default
variables are initially not at their steady state values and/or because
 the 
\emph on
exogenous
\emph default
 variables are not at their steady state values.
 We talk of an 
\emph on
impulse response
\emph default
 when the economy starts at the steady state, but some exogenous variables
 
\emph on
temporarily
\emph default
 deviate from the steady state following some converging auto-regressive
 process.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is also called an MIT shock.
 A shock in a model with perfect foresight is to some degree a contradiction
 in terms.
 The assumption is that even though the agents experiences a shock, they
 expect that there will never be a shock again.
 Accounting for expecting of future shocks is much more complicated.
 Some realism can be mimicked by studying impulse response to shocks about
 the future, which when the future comes never materialized as a new opposite
 signed shock negates it.
 Multiple shocks arriving sequentially can also be studied.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We simplify the model and the resulting equation system by writing it in
 terms of a 
\emph on
ordered series of block
\emph default
.
 We start from a set of 
\emph on
exogenous 
\emph default
variables (e.g.
 variables determined in the foreign economy) and a set of 
\emph on
unknown
\emph default
 variables.
 Each block then takes in the path of some variables, return the path of
 other variables, and imply 
\emph on
targets
\emph default
, which must be zero if the model equations are satisfied.
 Each block can use the unknown variables and output variables of previous
 blocks as input variables.
 In the end we collect all the targets.
 The 
\emph on
number of unknown variables
\emph default
 must equal the 
\emph on
number of target variables
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve the model, we must first find the steady state.
 As explained in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Steady-state"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, this can be done by manually choosing values for a selection of the endogenous
 variables and the deriving the rest from closed form expressions or solving
 sub-systems with a numerical equation system solver.
 Next, we solve for the equilibrium path again using a numerical equation
 system solver.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The block structure and ordering is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 unique.
 If a different set of unknowns is chosen, a different ordering of blocks
 must also be chosen.
 If an additional variable is considered an 
\emph on
unknown, 
\emph default
an additional equation must be considered a target instead of being used
 to calculate a output.
 In the limit, all variables can be considered as unknowns and all equations
 as targets.
 This is inefficient as the number of variables can be very large.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Modeling systems such as GAMS can combined with a state-of-the-art solver
 such as CONOOPT automatically analyze the structure of the equation system
 and thereby ripe the benefits we get from manually ordering the blocks.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
On CES technology
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:On-CES-technology"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The assumption of CES technology is used repeatedly in the model.
 It is therefore beneficial to recap it briefly.
 Consider a firm producing good 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 using good 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j}$
\end_inset

 with a CES technology.
 Input prices are 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{j}$
\end_inset

 and the output price is 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 The firm is a price taker in all markets.
 The 
\emph on
profit maximization
\emph default
 problem of the firm is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\max_{X_{i},X_{j}}PX-P_{i}X_{i}-P_{j}X_{j}\text{ s.t. }X=\Gamma\left(\mu_{i}^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}X_{i}^{\frac{\sigma-1}{\sigma}}+\mu_{j}^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}X_{j}^{\frac{\sigma-1}{\sigma}}\right)^{\frac{\sigma}{\sigma-1}},\,\,\,\mu_{i}+\mu_{j}=1,\,\mu_{i},\sigma,\Gamma>0,\,\sigma\neq1\label{eq:CES}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The generic 
\emph on
first order condition
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & =P\mu_{i}^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}X_{i}^{\frac{\sigma-1}{\sigma}-1}\Gamma\left(\mu_{i}^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}X_{i}^{\frac{\sigma-1}{\sigma}}+\mu_{j}^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}X_{j}^{\frac{\sigma-1}{\sigma}}\right)^{\frac{\sigma}{\sigma-1}-1}-P_{i}\Leftrightarrow\nonumber \\
P_{i} & =P\mu_{i}^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}X_{i}^{-\frac{1}{\sigma}}\Gamma\left(\mu_{i}^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}X_{i}^{\frac{\sigma-1}{\sigma}}+\mu_{j}^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}X_{j}^{\frac{\sigma-1}{\sigma}}\right)^{\frac{1}{\sigma-1}}\Leftrightarrow\nonumber \\
P_{i} & =P\mu_{i}^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}X_{i}^{-\frac{1}{\sigma}}\Gamma^{\frac{\sigma-1}{\sigma}}X^{\frac{1}{\sigma}}\Leftrightarrow\nonumber \\
X_{i} & =\mu_{i}\left(\frac{P}{P_{i}}\right)^{\sigma}\Gamma^{\sigma-1}X.\label{eq:CES_FOC_i}
\end{align}

\end_inset

As the production technology has constant return-to-scale, there are infinitely
 many solutions to the FOCs.
 They all satisfy that inputs are used in proportion as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{X_{i}}{X_{j}}=\frac{\mu_{i}}{\mu_{j}}\left(\frac{P_{j}}{P_{i}}\right)^{\sigma}\label{eq:FOCs_combined}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Assuming 
\emph on
free entry
\emph default
, and thus 
\emph on
zero profits
\emph default
, the output price is uniquely determined from the input prices as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & =PX-P_{i}X_{i}-P_{j}X_{j}\Leftrightarrow\nonumber \\
P & =\frac{P_{i}X_{i}+P_{j}X_{j}}{X}\nonumber \\
 & =\mu_{i}\left(\frac{P}{P_{i}}\right)^{\sigma}\Gamma^{\sigma-1}P_{i}+\mu_{j}\left(\frac{P}{P_{j}}\right)^{\sigma}\Gamma^{\sigma-1}P_{j}\Leftrightarrow\nonumber \\
\left(\Gamma P\right)^{1-\sigma} & =\mu_{i}P_{i}^{1-\sigma}+\mu_{j}P_{j}^{1-\sigma}\Leftrightarrow\nonumber \\
P & =\frac{1}{\Gamma}\left(\mu_{i}P_{i}^{1-\sigma}+\mu_{j}P_{j}^{1-\sigma}\right)^{\frac{1}{1-\sigma}}.\label{eq:CES_P}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Blocks
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Blocks"

\end_inset


\end_layout

